\end{gathered}
$$

In this equation, we have used $\left(\frac{\partial S}{\partial T}\right)_{p}=\frac{1}{T} c_{\mathrm{p}}$, $\left(\frac{\partial S}{\partial p}\right)_{T}=-\left(\frac{\partial V}{\partial T}\right)_{p}$ and $\frac{\mathrm{d} p}{\mathrm{~d} T}=\frac{\Delta S}{\Delta V}$. Introducing the latent heat of phase transition at equilibrium $L^{\beta \alpha}=T \Delta S=T\left(S^{\beta}-S^{\alpha}\right)$, the above expression can be reformulated as

$$
\frac{\mathrm{d}^{2} p}{\mathrm{~d} T^{2}}=\frac{\Delta c_{\mathrm{p}}}{T \Delta V}-\frac{2 L^{\beta \alpha}}{T(\Delta V)^{2}} \Delta\left(\frac{\partial V}{\partial T}\right)_{p}-\frac{\left(L^{\beta \alpha}\right)^{2}}{T^{2} (\Delta V)^{3}} \Delta\left(\frac{\partial V}{\partial p}\right)_{T}
$$

